Done. Here's a summary of the solution.

## Approach

`build_fst.py` builds a **compact, rule-based FST** rather than memorizing training pairs — which is the right call here because the task only requires generalizing to unseen *lemma+feature* combinations (the lemmas themselves are always seen, so memorization gives zero benefit on held-out data).

**Analysis of the morphology** showed Cebuano verb inflection is prefix-based: each lemma carries a class prefix (`mo-`, `ma-`, `mag-`, `man-`) followed by a stem, and each feature bundle swaps that prefix while copying the stem. The rules I extracted:

| feature | mo- | ma- | mag- | man- |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| NFIN/FUT | identity (copy lemma) | | | |
| PST | ni- | na- | nag- | nan- |
| PRS | nag-(‑) | na- | nag- | nan- |
| PROG;PRS | ning-(‑) | na- | nag- | nagpan- |
| PRF;PST | na- | na- | nag- | napan- |

Plus a hyphen inserted before vowel-initial stems for `mo-` present/progressive (`moadto → nag-adto`), and identity for prefix-less lemmas (`aduna`, `daw`). Branch prefixes are made mutually exclusive (the `ma-` stem is constrained not to start with `g`/`n`) so the transducer stays **functional** — exactly one output per input.

## Implementation
Built with PyFoma's `FST.re`, using quoting so every character and `[TAG]` is an atomic symbol, `defined` sub-networks (`$Sig`, `$Stem`, `$Vow`, `$Cons`) for the copy loops, then `determinize().minimize()`. Saved via `to_fomastring()` → `test.foma`.

## Results
- **30 states** (very compact — secondary goal met).
- **Fully functional**, exactly one output for all 582 seen-lemma × feature combos.
- **Dev: 51/58 (87.9%)**, **Test: 96/111 (86.5%)** — consistent with the 87.4% training-reproduction, confirming clean generalization.

The remaining errors are genuinely lexically-conditioned choices — chiefly `PRF;PST` `na-` vs `naka-` (the abilitative/completive "managed to" distinction, e.g. `mokaon→nakakaon`) and a few irregular lemmas (`mohimo→nakaya`). I verified there is **no surface signal** correlating na/naka with any other paradigm cell, so the majority rule (`na-`, 72% within that cell) is the accuracy ceiling. I used 1 of 10 grader runs; further runs wouldn't help since these residual choices are unpredictable and the held-out data can't be inspected to tune them.

